North Korea says it will “never” disarm unilaterally without trust
The North Korean foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepened their distrust of the United States and it was not possible for the country to unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s Annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant measures to show its goodwill” over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear testing facilities, and vowing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear weapons technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding response from the United States," he said.
“Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances, there is no chance that we will unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a phased approach to nuclear power that would lead to North Korea being rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statement seemed significant, as it did not reject a unilateral nuclear solution altogether as Pyongyang previously did.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim promised to work towards “the dismantling of nuclear weapons on the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the Korean War of 1950-53, but the US has said that Pyongyang must first decommission its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also declined negotiations to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘decommissioning first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its purpose by coercion and even objects to the ‘declaration to end the war’,” Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can get us on our knees is a dream come true for those people who lack knowledge of us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions deepen our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the US leaders highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
The minister instead pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If the party in this issue of nuclear disarmament were South Korea and not the United States, the Korean peninsula's nuclear disarmament would not have reached such a deadlock."
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s future capability to reach the U.S. mainland with rockets was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
This year in the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, commended Kim for his courage to take action for disarmament, but it said that much work remains to be done and that sanctions must remain until North Korea is disarmed.
