A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed area picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation advisor for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important to bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forest land for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects nests and loss of habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can aircraft and certain chemical treatments of building materials as well as attacks from domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technology to find insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
