Algae flowering: Lower levels in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in concentrations of algae bloom for parts of the area around Tampa Bay.
According to the Commission, uneven blooms are reported in the areas around the major municipalities of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which may indicate decreased levels.
The algae bloom extends along more than 20 miles of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee.
Spots can be seen about one and a half miles out into the sea outside the big municipality of Hillsborough, but in fewer places compared to last week.
Algae blooming has also been observed in the large municipality of Pasco.
Medium concentrations in or off the coast of Pinellas have been reported over the past week; off the coast of Hillsborough low to high concentrations, background concentrations to high concentrations in Manatee, background concentrations to high concentrations in or off the coast of Sarasota, background concentrations to medium concentrations in or off the coast of Lee, and low concentrations in Collier.
Reports of respiratory irritation continue to come from the major municipalities of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There were no reports of respiratory irritation in northwest Florida last week.
